column1: Who will win the upcoming election for the United Kingdom's Labour Party?
column6: ['Leader Entry/Exit', 'Elections and Referenda']
column11: Jeremy Corbyn maintained his leadership of the Labor Party in September's election (CNN, The Guardian). Since "Leave" won the Brexit referendum, Labour Party leader Jeremy Corbyn has come under intense criticism and is now facing a tough race for leadership of his party (BBC, Wall Street Journal). The results of the election are scheduled to be released on 24 September 2016. Recommended Questions Before 1 July 2017, will Scotland set a date for another referendum on independence from the United Kingdom? When will the United Kingdom invoke Article 50 of the Lisbon Treaty? What will the end-of-day closing value for the British pound against the US dollar be on 30 December 2016?

column6: That's it folks! 'Labour leadership hopeful Owen Smith, asked in an interview in the final hours of the campaign whether he would serve in a Jeremy Corbyn shadow cabinet, said: "I won't be serving in Jeremy's cabinet but I will do what I've always done which is be Labour, vote Labour, loyally serve this party, make sure that from the backbenches I continue to make the arguments I've made during this campaign." '
All reports are that Corbyn will win by a comfortable margin.

Poll carried out by YouGov shows clear win by Corbyn. "Corbyn secured 62 per cent of the vote - 24 points ahead of his rival and more than two points more than his own vote last year." [1]. It is interesting, however, the fact that many Labour supporters voted for Brexit was attributed partly to Corbyn's failure to convince Labour to vote for Remain. Moreover, although his leadership is being challenged by his MPs, he retains such a strong support by the party base. Are there similarities with the Trump phenomenon - the public votes against to what it considers to be the wish (or will) of the establishment?

His fellow MP's had the vote of no-confidence post Brexit but this is not shared by party members around Britain. The latest polls give mr Smith no chance and also the bookmakers give a Corbyn victory more than 85% chance. I move up but remain below polls and bookies.

There really has been no polling of Labour's "selectorate" since the race began in earnest. The assumption of another Corbyn victory is based on little real analysis. Just as the Corbyn phenomenon crept up almost entirely unnoticed by the mainstream press, I think it is fair to suggest that Labour members and registered supporters might turn towards another, electable alternative now that Corbyn has served his purpose by moving the entire party further leftwards.
Jeremy Corbyn is hands-down the favourite with members 'on the ground' however the party hierarchy is doing all in its power to purge Corbyn supporters.

The Corbyn camp must be pretty confident of victory if they are prepared to brief against the leadership north of the border. http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14709297.Labour_big_guns_turn_on_Dugdale/

We seem to be living an a era of the uber-protest vote, where enthusiasts vote for a dream (their dream, maybe our nightmare) candidate who has no possibility of actually doing whatever they say they will do. Corbyn, Trump, Brexit all fall into this category). At some point voters will presumably switch to candidates that have policies that have some chance of being carried out, but this will probably not happen in the next 4 weeks.

The voting is rigged by the Labour Party system that gives votes to party members and the unions that outweigh the votes from MPs. The parliamentary party seems out of step from the membership and we're more likely to see MPs defect to form a modern labour party rather than accept Corbyn's re-epection as leader
Owen Smith has very low press coverage. The 'weapons' the Labour party can use against Jeremy Cornyn have already been used and failed to be effective. If anything they have strengthened JC position.
The Labour Party members appear to be firmly behind the incumbent with many upset by the behaviour of rebel Labour MPs, it seems there is little prospect of a change.

I believe that Jeremy Corbyn retains the support of most of the party membership, and unless the rules are changed he will win the leadership election - hence the 80/15 split in his favour. There is an outside chance that the split between the national and Westminster parties will result in some unforseen development - hence the 5% for None of the above.
Even with the High Court judgement on new members going against him (as both sides seem to agree), he still has a solid base in the party.
